],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"A doctor who helped build Palm Springs","body":"Florilla White first saw Palm Springs in 1912, when the village held just fifteen buildings, and arrived to stay the next year with her sister Cornelia. The two bought the original Palm Springs Hotel and made themselves fixtures of the desert town she helped grow."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"She escaped revolution on a railroad hand car","body":"During the Mexican Revolution in 1913, White and her sister fled by securing a railroad hand car and pumping it over stretches where the ties had burned away. They reached Mazatlán and sailed to San Diego."},{"number":3,"category":"social_reform","header":"She raised a nursing corps against the flu","body":"As Palm Springs's village health officer during the First World War, White founded a volunteer nursing group she called the Nightingales to meet the 1918 influenza epidemic. A dedicated horsewoman, she rode the desert canyons with Cahuilla guides and, like her sister, never wore skirts."}],"education":[{"school_name":"Boston University School of Medicine","dates":"1908","type":"medical","notes":"M.D., June 6, 1908."}],"slug":"florilla-white-1871"},"HD1613":{"id":"HD1613","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":9,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1873},"death":{"year":1947},"parents":{"father_id":"X00514","mother_id":"HD1608"},"marriages":[],"tags":[],"sources":[],"naming_inspiration":{"name_element":"Pierrepont","notes":"Named \"Pierrepont\" honoring mother Anna Maria Pierrepont White's (HD1608) ancestry."},"gender":"female","notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Pierrepont White","first_name":"Mary","middle_name":"Pierrepont","maiden_name":"White","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"mary-white-1873"},"HD1536":{"id":"HD1536","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":9,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00514","mother_id":"HD1608"},"tags":["died_unmarried","educator"],"sources":[{"short":"Moffat, R. Burnham. Pierrepont Genealogies from Norman times to 1913 (1913)"},{"short":"Brooklyn Historical Society: Pierrepont Family Papers ARC.263"}],"birth":{"year":1874},"death":{"year":1961},"gender":"female","marriages":[],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["education","exploration"],"notable_blurb":"Palm Springs pioneer and civic founder","primary_url":"https://cvindependent.com/2023/07/cv-history-the-adventurous-white-sisters-made-their-mark-on-early-palm-springs/","primary_url_label":"Coachella Valley Independent"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Cornelia Butler White","first_name":"Cornelia","middle_name":"Butler","maiden_name":"White","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780692030/Screenshot_2026-06-05_at_1.40.18_PM_tikv7c.png","photo_notes":"Palm Springs Historical Society."},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST012"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"Co-founded what became Palm Springs Art Museum","body":"Cornelia White co-founded the institution that became the Palm Springs Art Museum, deeding her property along Tahquitz Canyon Way to the Palm Springs Desert Museum in 1947. The main-floor gallery of the present Palm Springs Art Museum is dedicated to her. She and her sister Florilla had earlier co-purchased the original Palm Springs Hotel in 1913 and in 1915 bought an entire block at the Palm Canyon Drive corner for seventy-five dollars — selling it to a hotel developer in the 1930s for seven thousand."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"Europe, Pacific Northwest mines, Arctic Circle, Nile","body":"Cornelia left the family farm at age eighteen and built an explicit adventurer life: a year in Europe 1894-1895, a mining expedition in the Pacific Northwest, travel above the Arctic Circle, and sailing up the Nile River in Egypt. The travel was unusual for an American woman of her generation. In her Palm Springs home she built a stone house half-buried in the ground for coolness — a chosen architectural pragmatism over fashion."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Taught plumbing and carpentry at North Dakota, 1911","body":"Around 1911, Cornelia White taught plumbing and carpentry at the University of North Dakota — an extraordinary teaching assignment for a woman of that era, when both fields were almost exclusively male trades. Neither she nor her sister Florilla wore skirts; their refusal to do so was contemporary chronicled as 'the common-sense attire of a very modest woman in refinement and culture' that 'proved that an active outdoor life in chaparral country can be the life for a lady.'"},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Born Canaseraga NY 1874, died Banning CA 1961","body":"Cornelia Butler White was born July 2, 1874 in Canaseraga, Allegany County New York. She died September 28, 1961 in Banning, Riverside County California at age eighty-seven. She is buried at Welwood Murray Cemetery in Palm Springs."}],"slug":"cornelia-white-1874"},"HD1614":{"id":"HD1614","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":f